In this statement, the President commemorates Holocaust Remembrance Day and pays tribute to the memory of those who suffered and died during the Holocaust. He emphasizes that even after more than six decades, the grief and outrage over the Nazis' murder of six million Jews and others has not diminished. The President highlights the significance of the first Nuremberg trial and Adolf Eichmann's trial in promoting international justice and holding perpetrators of genocide accountable. He stresses the importance of confronting Holocaust denial and genocidal ideologies, and stopping the spread of hate in the present. The President also calls for listening to and caring for the last living survivors, camp liberators, and witnesses to the Holocaust, and honoring the courage and dignity of those who perished. He emphasizes the responsibility to ensure that the world never forgets and to stand up against intolerance and injustice.